==German==

===Etymology===
Originally {{prefix|de|n|immer}}, thus the same construct as English {{m|en|ever}} and {{m|en|never}}. Later on there has been interference by unrelated dialectal contractions of {{m|de|nicht mehr}}, as which the word is interpreted by most contemporary speakers.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/ˈnɪmər/}}
* {{audio|de|De-nimmer.ogg|Audio}}

===Adverb===
{{head|de|adverb}}

# {{lb|de|regional|chiefly|southern Germany|Austria}} [[no]] [[more]], [[no longer]]
# {{lb|de|regional|chiefly|southern Germany|Austria}} [[never again]]
# {{lb|de|archaic|or|poetic|literary}} [[never]], at no time
#* {{rfdate|de}}, Espenbaum, Paul Celan:
#*: Meiner Mutter Haar ward '''nimmer''' weiß.

====Usage notes====
* In northern Germany and many parts of central Germany, the word is used mainly in some set phrases such as {{m|de|nie und nimmer||never ever}}. Otherwise, it sounds archaic or poetic. It is used more readily in southern Germany and Austria, meaning “no more” or “never again”. The original sense “never, at no time” is now rare.

